                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.6363/110.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Rear Admiral Sir <persName type="from">C. Cradock</persName>
                        to the <gloss type="to">British Ambassador at Washington</gloss>.</hi>
                    <note n="96" xml:id="d1131fn96">Handed to the Department of State by the British
                        Ambassador May 7, 1914.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vera Cruz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 7, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>From the conditions known to me and judging by my own experience I think it would
                    be rash if American citizens relied too implicitly on Mexican assurances and
                    returned now to the oil-fields. Their return might be misunderstood, and a
                    situation might arise which would imperil all foreign interests.</p>
                <closer>[Unsigned.]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
